ghton|date=13 June 2019|access-date=24 August 2019|work=SportsMax}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://barbadostoday.bb/2019/06/13/strong-windies-a-teams-named/|title=Strong Windies A teams named|date=13 June 2019|access-date=24 August 2019|work=Barbados Today}}</ref> but after an injury to Brathwaite he stepped in to captain the first two matches as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/cricketnext/news/west-indies-selectors-make-changes-to-a-squad-as-brathwaite-dowrich-injured-2243349.html|title=West Indies Selectors Make Changes To 'A' Squad as Brathwaite, Dowrich Injured|date=25 July 2019|access-date=24 August 2019|work=Cricket Next}}</ref> Brooks led from the front with half centuries in both of the first two matches,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/19366/report/1190804/west-indies-a-vs-india-a-1st-unofficial-test-india-a-in-west-indies-2019|title=Recent Match Report - West Indies A vs India A 1st unofficial Test 2019|date=26 July 2019|access-date=24 August 2019|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/firstcricket/sports-news/india-a-vs-west-indies-a-montcin-hodge-shamarh-brooks-strike-fifties-to-take-hosts-to-2435-on-day-1-of-second-unofficial-test-7094431.html|title=India A vs West Indies A: Montcin Hodge, Shamarh Brooks strike fifties to take hosts to 243/5 on Day 1 of second unofficial Test|date=1 August 2019|access-date=24 August 2019|work=First Post}}</ref> He was then again named in the West Indies' Test squad, this time for their [[Indian cricket team in the West Indies and the United States in 2019|series against India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1197123.html|title=Rahkeem Cornwall makes it to West Indies Test squad|date=10 August 2019|access-date=10 August 2019|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/uncapped-rahkeem-cornwall-shamarh-brooks-in-windies-squad-for-india-test-series/|title=Uncapped Rahkeem Cornwall, Shamarh Brooks in Windies squad for India Test series|author=Bijoy|date=10 August 2019|access-date=24 August 2019|work=CricTracker}}</ref>\n\nHe made his Test debut for the West Indies against [[India national cricket team|India]] on 22 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1188628.html |title=1st Test, ICC World Test Championship at North Sound, Aug 22-26 2019 |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, in the one-off Test [[West Indian cricket team against Afghanistan in India in 2019\u201320|against Afghanistan]], Brooks scored his first century in Test cricket, with 111 runs.<ref name=\"CB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/111037/shamarh-brooks-maiden-ton-inflates-lead-to-90 |title=Shamarh Brooks' maiden ton inflates lead to 90 |work=CricBuzz |accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Twenty20 franchise cricket==\nBrooks played for the [[St Kitts & Nevis Patriots]] in the [[Caribbean Premier League]], the top-level Twenty20 league in the West Indies, for two seasons in [[2016 Caribbean Premier League|2016]] and [[2017 Caribbean Premier League|2017]]. He played 4 matches in each season, and across them both scored 119 runs at an average of 23.80 with a strike-rate of 120.20.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/caribbean-premier-league-2016/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=11003;team=5543;type=tournament|title=Caribbean Premier League, 2016 - St Kitts and Nevis Patriots Cricket Team Records & Stats|access-date=24 August 2019|work=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/caribbean-premier-league-2017/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=11754;team=5543;type=tournament|title=Caribbean Premier League, 2017 - St Kitts and Nevis Patriots Cricket Team Records & Stats|access-date=24 August 2019|work=ESPncricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo}}\n\n{{St Kitts and Nevis Patriots Squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooks, Sharmarh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:West Indies Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Barbadian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Barbados cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Michael, Barbados]]\n[[Category:St Kitts and Nevis Patriots cricketers]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shamarh_Brooks"}
{"title_page": "Sir Christopher Powell, 4th Baronet", "text_new": "'''Sir Christopher Powell, 4th Baronet'''  (c. 1690\u20131742), of Wierton House, in Boughton Monchelsea, Kent, was a British Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1735 to 1741.\n\nPowell was the second son of Barnham Powell and his wife Elizabeth Clitherow, daughter of James Clitherow of Boston, Middlesex and grandson of Sir Nathaniel Powell, 2nd Baronet  of Wierton. He succeeded his brother to the [[Powell baronets|baronetcy]] in 1708.<ref name=Cokayne3>{{Citation| editor-last=Cokayne| editor-first=George Edward |year=1903 | title= Complete Baronetage volume 3 (1649-1664),  | url=   https://archive.org/details/cu31924092524390/page/n213 | volume=3| location=Exeter | publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages=| accessdate = 9 October 2018}}</ref> He matriculated at  Queen's, Oxford on 15 July 1709, aged 19. <ref name=ALUM>{{cite web |url =  https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp1181-1208 |title= Popham-Price in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714   pp.1181-1208 | author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= British History Online| accessdate =  2 January 2019 }}</ref> In. 1728, he married Frances Newington. \n \nPowell was returned unopposed as a Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]] on 19 February 1735 in succession to Lord Vane. He voted with the Opposition. He did not stand in [[1741 British general election]]. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/powell-sir-christopher-1690-1742| title=POWELL, Sir Christopher, 4th Bt. (?1690-1742), of Wierton House, in Boughton Monchelsea, Kent. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nPowell died without issue on 5 July 1742.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Vane, 1st Viscount Vane|The Viscount Vane]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Edward Dering, 5th Baronet|Sir Edward Dering]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]]\n | years =   1735\u2013[[1741 British general election|1741]]\n | with  =  [[Sir Edward Dering, 5th Baronet|Sir Edward Dering]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Roger Twisden, 5th Baronet|Sir Roger Twisden]] | after2 = [[Sir Edward Dering, 5th Baronet|Sir Edward Dering]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before= Sir Nathaniel Powell, 3rd Baronet\n}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Powell  baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Ewhurst ) | years=1708-1742''' }}\n{{s-aft | after = Baronetcy extinct\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Powell, Sir Christopher, 4th Baronet }}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1742 deaths]]\n [[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n [[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Christopher Powell, 4th Baronet'''  (c. 1690\u20131742), of Wierton House, in Boughton Monchelsea, Kent, was a British Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1735 to 1741.\n\nPowell was the second son of Barnham Powell and his wife Elizabeth Clitherow, daughter of James Clitherow of Boston, Middlesex and grandson of Sir Nathaniel Powell, 2nd Baronet  of Wierton. He succeeded his brother to the [[Powell baronets|baronetcy]] in 1708.<ref name=Cokayne3>{{Citation| editor-last=Cokayne| editor-first=George Edward |year=1903 | title= Complete Baronetage volume 3 (1649-1664),  | url=   https://archive.org/details/cu31924092524390/page/n213 | volume=3| location=Exeter | publisher=William Pollard and Co| pages=| accessdate = 9 October 2018}}</ref> He matriculated at  Queen\u2019s, Oxford on 15 July 1709, aged 19. <ref name=ALUM>{{cite web |url =  https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp1181-1208 |title= Popham-Price in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714   pp.1181-1208 | author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= British History Online| accessdate =  2 January 2019 }}</ref> In. 1728, he married Frances Newington. \n \nPowell was returned unopposed as a Whig [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]] on 19 February 1735 in succession to Lord Vane. He voted with the Opposition. He did not stand in [[1741 British general election]]. <ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/powell-sir-christopher-1690-1742| title=POWELL, Sir Christopher, 4th Bt. (?1690-1742), of Wierton House, in Boughton Monchelsea, Kent. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nPowell died without issue on 5 July 1742.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Vane, 1st Viscount Vane|The Viscount Vane]]\n | before2 = [[Sir Edward Dering, 5th Baronet|Sir Edward Dering]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]]\n | years =   1735\u2013[[1741 British general election|1741]]\n | with  =  [[Sir Edward Dering, 5th Baronet|Sir Edward Dering]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Roger Twisden, 5th Baronet|Sir Roger Twisden]] | after2 = [[Sir Edward Dering, 5th Baronet|Sir Edward Dering]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|en-bt}}\n{{S-bef| before= Sir Nathaniel Powell, 3rd Baronet\n}}\n{{S-ttl| title=[[Powell  baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Ewhurst ) | years=1708-1742''' }}\n{{s-aft | after = Baronetcy extinct\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Powell, Sir Christopher, 4th Baronet }}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1742 deaths]]\n [[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n [[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of England]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Christopher_Powell,_4th_Baronet"}
{"title_page": "Nacho Varga", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{all plot|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #133E51\n| name               = Nacho Varga\n| series             = [[Better Call Saul]]\n| image              = NachoVargaBCS.jpg\n| caption            = [[Michael Mando]] as Nacho Varga in a promotional poster for [[Better Call Saul (season 4)|''Better Call Saul''{{'}}s fourth season]]\n| first              = \"[[Mijo]]\" (2015)\n| last               = \n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Vince Gilligan]]\n* [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]\n}}\n| portrayer          = [[Michael Mando]]\n| full_name          = Ignacio Varga\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Tuco's Lieutenant\n* Hector's Lieutenant\n* Criminal associate of [[Gus Fring]]\n}}\n| family             = Manuel Varga (father)\n| nationality        = Mexican\n| home               = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], United States\n}}\n'''Ignacio <!-- do not shoehorn Nacho here per [[WP:HYPOCORISM]], since it is a common diminutive of Ignacio (see [[Hypocorism#Spanish]]) -->Varga''' is a fictional character who appears in the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', a prequel [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. He is portrayed by [[Michael Mando]] and was created by [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]].\n\nNacho is a quiet and intelligent member of the Salamanca drug organization. He cares deeply for the well-being of his honest, hard-working father, Manuel. He befriends [[Saul Goodman|Jimmy McGill]] after Jimmy helps clear him of kidnapping charges. When the Salamancas seek to use his father's shop as a front for the drug ring, Nacho attempts to kill [[Hector Salamanca]], the family patriarch, by switching his medication, but this is discovered by [[Gus Fring]], who runs the rival drug trade. Nacho is forced to be a mole for Gus within the Salamancas, which is further complicated when the cartel sends the shrewd [[Lalo Salamanca]] to oversee operations.\n\n== Concept and development ==\n[[Michael Mando]] said that he had been approached through his agent from ''Better Call Saul''{{'s}} casting directors about being in the show. After sending in an audition tape, he was flown to Los Angeles to meet with showrunners [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]] and perform a screen test. For Mando, he said it was \"love at first sight\" in working with the pair in how well they provided direction and feedback, and was notified about getting the part a few weeks later.<ref name=\"abq mando\" /> To prepare for Nacho, Mando spent time watching crime and criminology documentaries to understand the motivations of criminals, as well as catching up on the whole of ''Breaking Bad'', which he had not yet watched in its entirety before. Mando considered Nacho to be \"extremely intelligent and patient\" and would be a character that would have growth over the course of the show.<ref name=\"abq mando\">{{Cite news |last=Gomez |first=Adrian |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/544900/better-call-saul-star-delves-into-role.html |title=\u2018Better Call Saul\u2019s bad guy looks forward to season two |date=February 22, 2015 |work=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |access-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410180943/https://www.abqjournal.com/544900/better-call-saul-star-delves-into-role.html |archive-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Mando said that the showrunners gave little direction to the character, and instead \"They wanted to see what I would bring to the character\", allowing him to develop Nacho himself.<ref name=\"postmedia mando\" /> For part of that, he explored elements of [[Maya civilization|Mayan]] and [[Aztecs|Aztec]] cultures to bring to the character. He also brought some of the supervisial traits of his ''[[Orphan Black]]'' character Vic Schmidt into Nacho.<ref name=\"postmedia mando\">{{Cite web |url=https://o.canada.com/entertainment/television/quebec-actor-michael-mando-plays-better-call-saul-villian |title=Quebec actor Michael Mando plays Better Call Saul {{sic|nolink=y|villian}} |last=Strachan |first=Alex |date=February 4, 2015 |website=[[Postmedia News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812060609/http://o.canada.com/entertainment/television/quebec-actor-michael-mando-plays-better-call-saul-villian |archive-date=August 12, 2018 |access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMando said that initially Nacho was going to have a larger role with Jimmy in the first season, being the season's \"[[Big Bad|big bad]]\", but as Gilligan and Gould wrote out the season, they made the character of [[Chuck McGill]] more of an antagonist for Jimmy, and so Nacho was placed on a slower path to be developed in later seasons. Mando said he felt this helped fit Nacho's character, waiting patiently for the right opportunity to make a move to get ahead.<ref name=\"vulture ignacio\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/03/better-call-saul-michael-mando-nacho-dilemma.html |title=Better Call Saul\u2019s Michael Mando on Nacho\u2019s Dilemma, His Bond With Mike, and the Mystery of Ignacio |last=Herzog |first=Kenny |date=March 7, 2016 |website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401045706/https://www.vulture.com/2016/03/better-call-saul-michael-mando-nacho-dilemma.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/better-call-saul-michael-mando-was-supposed-to-be-season-1s-big-bad-heres-why-they-changed-that.html/ |title='Better Call Saul': Michael Mando Was Supposed to be Season 1's Big Bad. Here's Why They Changed That |last=Topel |first=Fred |date=March 9, 2020 |website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311061141/https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/better-call-saul-michael-mando-was-supposed-to-be-season-1s-big-bad-heres-why-they-changed-that.html/ |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Character biography ==\n[[File:Michael Mando by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|right|200px|[[Michael Mando]] portrays Nacho Varga in ''Better Call Saul'']]\nLittle is known of Nacho's background before the events of ''Better Call Saul''. While he spends some of his time helping his father Manuel with his [[upholstery]] business, most of Nacho's time is assisting in the Salamanca family's drug ring, which he does not speak of to his father.\n\n=== Season 1 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 1)}}\nWhile attempting to represent the Kettlemans, a family accused of embezzling $1.6 million, [[Saul Goodman|Jimmy McGill]] has a run-in with [[Tuco Salamanca]]. Tuco  has Nacho and other associates drag Jimmy to the desert to kill him. Nacho believes Jimmy's plea that he is a lawyer and convinces Tuco that killing an attorney would result in police scrutiny of the Salamanca family's drug business, so Tuco lets Jimmy go. Nacho approaches Jimmy about stealing the money from the Kettlemans, but Jimmy refuses. He warns the Kettlemans, who disappear from their home.  Nacho is the prime suspect and is arrested. He coerces Jimmy into helping clear his name and Jimmy locates the Kettlemans, which leads to Nacho's release.\n\nNacho engages in a side deal with Daniel Wormald (\"Pryce\"), who wants to sell pills stolen from the pharmaceutical company where he works. Daniel brings [[Mike Ehrmantraut]] as a bodyguard. When Nacho's payment is $20 short, Mike insists he pay the full amount. As Daniel and Mike leave, Mike explains that he knew Nacho was conducting the transaction without the Salamancas' knowledge and so had an incentive to make sure the deal went smoothly.\n\n=== Season 2 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 2)}}\nDaniel uses his drug money to buy a flashy [[Hummer]]. Mike refuses to participate in the next deal, so Daniel goes alone. Nacho takes the opportunity to learn Daniel's name and address. He later breaks into Daniel's house and steals the money back, along with a valuable collection of baseball cards. Daniel reports the collection's theft to the police, who discover an empty hiding place where Daniel hid the stolen drugs. Mike realizes his involvement will be uncovered if police continue to investigate, so he convinces Nacho to give Daniel the cards and $10,000 in exchange for the Hummer.\n\nNacho is impressed by Mike's candor and coolness under pressure.  As Tuco become increasingly volatile, potentially exposing the Salamanca organization, and the likelihood of his learning about Nacho's secret deals increases, Nacho decides to eliminate Tuco and tries to hire Mike to kill him.  Mike instead arranges a scenario where Tuco attacks him in view of police, leading to Tuco's arrest and conviction. [[Hector Salamanca]] has Nacho take Tuco's place in the organization. Mike becomes fearful that Hector may discover his role in removing Tuco from the family's operations.  He attempts to draw police attention to the Salamanca operation by hijacking one of the trucks used to smuggle drugs over the Mexican border, leaving the driver tied up at the side of the road and stealing the {{USD|250,000}} hidden in one of the tires. Nacho tells Mike that Hector covered up the hijacking by killing the Good Samaritan who stopped to aid the driver.\n\n=== Season 3 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 3)}}\nMike's actions lead to Hector looking for other routes to smuggle drugs, and he considers using Manuel's upholstery shop. Nacho objects, but fails to change Hector's mind.  To protect his father, Nacho reveals his involvement in the Salamanca organization. Manuel accepts Hector's initial payment after Nacho convinces him doing so is for his own safety. Nacho realizes Hector suffers from angina and decides to try to kill him by replacing his nitroglycerin with an ibuprofen [[placebo]] in the hopes of inducing a fatal heart attack.  Mike advises Nacho that if Hector dies, Nacho should immediately take the placebos from Hector and replace them with the real medication so that the cause of Hector's death won't be obvious.\n\nNacho succeeds in making the switch, but Hector does not die, so Nacho plans to shoot him.  Before he can act, Nacho is notified to attend a meeting with [[Gus Fring]], Juan Bolsa, and Hector. Bolsa informs Hector that cartel leader Don Eladio has decreed that since Hector's trucks are no longer viable for smuggling drugs, the cartel will make the transport of Hector's drugs via Gus's trucks a permanent arrangement. An outraged Hector has a stroke and falls to the ground unconscious.  Gus performs first aid while awaiting an ambulance, and succeeds in saving Hector's life, though he remains comatose.  Nacho takes the placebos from Hector and replaces them with the real medication.  Gus seems to realize that something is amiss, but says nothing.\n\n=== Season 4 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 4)}}\nBolsa tells Nacho that he and Arturo should run the Salamanca family while Hector is hospitalized.  Gus pays for Hector's specialized care to the point where his mental faculties are recovered and he can move the index finger of his right hand.  Gus reviews Hector's medical records and realizes there is no nitroglycerin in his system, meaning Nacho tried to kill him.  When Nacho and Arturo arrive at Gus' chicken farm to pick up their next cocaine shipment, Arturo takes six kilos instead of the agreed-upon five, as Nacho did on a previous occasion.  As they leave, Gus springs an ambush and suffocates Arturo with a plastic bag.  Gus reveals that he is aware of Nacho's attempt to kill Hector, and that if Nacho does not follow Gus' orders, Gus will inform the Salamancas.  Nacho, Victor, and Tyrus fake an ambush site on a remote road, shooting bullet holes in Nacho's car, setting the car on fire, and shooting Nacho.\n\nNacho is treated by veterinarian Dr. Caldera, who succeeds in saving his life.  Victor sells the drugs taken from Nacho to the Espinosas, a rival gang.  The Cousins arrive and Nacho falsely identifies the Espinosas as the ones who attacked him.  The Cousins attack the Espinosa compound, kill everyone inside, and recover the \"stolen\" drugs.  Nacho sees that by wiping out the Espinosas, Gus has secured more drug territory for himself, but does not yet see the full scope of Gus' plan.  Nacho goes to his father's house to recover, and Manuel takes him in despite being unhappy about Nacho's ties to the Salamancas.  After recovering, Nacho takes on a more prominent role in the Salamanca organization, but also keeps a safe with cash and fake Canadian IDs for himself and his father.  Nacho is surprised when Lalo Salamanca arrives to aid in running the business, and takes a stronger interest in the day-to-day details than Hector did.\n\n=== Season 5 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 5)}}\nUnder Gus' orders, Nacho replaces some of the Salamanca cocaine supply with inferior, locally produced methamphetamine.  Buyer complaints lead Lalo to meet with Gus and Juan Bolsa.  Gus presents a cover story about Werner Ziegler, of whose activities Lalo was partly aware.{{efn|from \"[[Winner (Better Call Saul)|Winner]]\"}}  Gus claims Werner was working on a legitimate construction project at the chicken farm and stole cocaine, which Gus then replaced with meth.  The story explains the events of which Lalo is aware&nbsp;\u2013 Werner's work for Gus and escape, Mike's pursuit, and Werner's death.  Lalo accepts Gus' story and apology, but remains suspicious.\n\nGus threatens Manuel's life in order to coerce Nacho into providing inside information on the Salamancas. When police identify a Salamanca drug house and arrest Domingo, Nacho sneaks over rooftops to recover the drug stash before police enter, which impresses Lalo, who begins to take Nacho into his confidence.  Lalo is concerned that Domingo will talk in jail, so he and Nacho arrange to secure Domingo's release by providing police information on Gus's dead drops. Nacho reports this plan to Gus.  Gus decides to keep the dead drops in place, despite the likely loss of $700,000 in cash, because removing them would reveal to Lalo that someone is providing inside information about the Salamancas.\n\nGus, Victor, and Mike meet with Nacho and Nacho pretends not to recognize Mike. He reports on Lalo's plan to give police the locations of Gus's street dealers and Gus tells Nacho to report to Mike from now on. Nacho attempts to warn Mike about Gus's ruthlessness, but Mike reminds Nacho that he warned Nacho about the risk Nacho was taking when he attempted to kill Hector Salamanca.{{efn|from \"[[Expenses (Better Call Saul)|Expenses]]\"}} Mike secretly points the police to Lalo's car and its connection to the murder of Fred, the money wire store clerk.{{efn|from \"[[Winner (Better Call Saul)|Winner]]\"}} Nacho calls Mike to report Lalo's location. Mike uses a police radio and pretends to be an officer requesting a check of Lalo's licence plate, which causes police to converge on Lalo while he is driving and detain him.\n\nFrom jail, Lalo instructs Nacho to further disrupt Gus's business activities by burning down one of his restaurants, information Nacho relays to Mike. To preserve Nacho's role as his mole in the Salamanca organization, Gus and Nacho vandalize his flagship restaurant and set off an explosion that burns it down. Nacho enlists Jimmy to represent Lalo. Gus desires Lalo's release, so Mike provides Jimmy information on the investigation he did of Lalo under an assumed name. Jimmy uses the details to secure Lalo's release on US$7 million cash bail. Lalo has Jimmy pick up the cash funds for bail from The Cousins at a remote location in the desert. On his way back, Jimmy is attacked by gunmen, but Mike was tracking him for Gus and kills all but one attacker. The surviving gunman escapes in the only attacker's vehicle that is still drivable. Mike's truck was also damaged, so Mike and Jimmy begin the drive back to Albuquerque in Jimmy's car. When the car breaks down, they push it over the edge of he road and walk cross-country to avoid the surviving gunman. After killing the surviving gunman and walking for two days in the desert, Jimmy and Mike make their way back to Albuquerque and Jimmy posts Lalo's bail. Jimmy says he was alone and his car broke down, so he walked cross-country so he would not risk losing the money. Lalo says he will return to Mexico to avoid police scrutiny. Mike reports on the attack to Gus, who realizes Juan Bolsa engineered the attack to protect Gus's business. Mike tells Gus that Nacho no longer wants to be his informant on the Salamanca organization, and express his unhappiness at Gus threatening Nacho's father to obtain Nacho's compliance. Gus refuses to part with a valuable asset, and Mike silently leaves his office.\n\nNacho informs Mike of Lalo's plan to return to Mexico. Lalo says goodbye to Hector and Nacho brings him to the same pickup site where Jimmy received the money. Instead of waiting for The Cousins, he searches for Jimmy's car. After finding it, he tells Nacho they are returning to Albuquerque. Mike calls to warn Jimmy just before Nacho and Lalo arrives at Kim and Jimmy's apartment. Nacho waits in his car while Lalo goes inside. Unseen by Nacho, Mike trains a sniper rifle on Lalo from a nearby rooftop. Lalo asks Jimmy to repeat the story of his desert trek several times, then reveals he found bullet holes in Jimmy's car. Kim tells Lalo that passersby probably shot at the car for fun and berates Lalo for not trusting Jimmy. Lalo appears satisfied with Kim's argument and departs. After Lalo gets back in Nacho's car, he tells Nacho they are going to Mexico, but not to the original pick up site.\n\n=== ''Breaking Bad'' ===\nNacho did not appear in ''Breaking Bad'', but is named in the second-season episode \"[[Better Call Saul (Breaking Bad)|Better Call Saul]]\", the same episode that introduced Saul Goodman. In the episode, [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] and [[Jesse Pinkman]] attempt to coerce Saul into representing Badger after Badger is arrested for selling drugs. Unaware of who his gun-wielding captors are, Saul tries to pin blame on \"Ignacio\", who was later confirmed by ''Breaking Bad'' and ''Better Call Saul'' producers to be Nacho Varga.<ref name=\"vulture ignacio\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nMando has received positive reviews for his portrayal of Nacho.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/10/michael-mando-better-call-saul-interview_n_6652668.html |title=Canadian Boy Makes Waves On 'Better Call Saul' |last=Jancelewicz |first=Chris |date=February 10, 2015 |website=[[HuffPost]] |location=Canada |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213090107/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/10/michael-mando-better-call-saul-interview_n_6652668.html |archive-date=February 13, 2015 |access-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notelist==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul/cast-crew/nacho-varga Nacho Varga] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Varga, Nacho}}\n[[Category:Better Call Saul characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional career criminals]]\n[[Category:Fictional gangsters]]\n[[Category:Fictional henchmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2015]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{all plot|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #133E51\n| name               = Nacho Varga\n| series             = [[Better Call Saul]]\n| image              = NachoVargaBCS.jpg\n| caption            = [[Michael Mando]] as Nacho Varga in a promotional poster for [[Better Call Saul (season 4)|''Better Call Saul''{{'}}s fourth season]]\n| first              = \"[[Mijo]]\" (2015)\n| last               = \n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Vince Gilligan]]\n* [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]\n}}\n| portrayer          = [[Michael Mando]]\n| full_name          = Ignacio Varga\n| occupation         = {{Plainlist|\n* Tuco's Lieutenant\n* Hector's Lieutenant\n* Criminal associate of [[Gus Fring]]\n}}\n| family             = Manuel Varga (father)\n| nationality        = Mexican\n| home               = [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], United States\n}}\n'''Ignacio <!-- do not shoehorn Nacho here per [[WP:HYPOCORISM]], since it is a common diminutive of Ignacio (see [[Hypocorism#Spanish]]) -->Varga''' is a fictional character who appears in the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', a prequel [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. He is portrayed by [[Michael Mando]] and was created by [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]].\n\nNacho is a quiet and intelligent member of the Salamanca drug organization. He cares deeply for the well-being of his honest, hard-working father, Manuel. He befriends [[Saul Goodman|Jimmy McGill]] after Jimmy helps clear him of kidnapping charges. When the Salamancas seek to use his father's shop as a front for the drug ring, Nacho attempts to kill [[Hector Salamanca]], the family patriarch, by switching his medication, but this is discovered by [[Gus Fring]], who runs the rival drug trade. Nacho is forced to be a mole for Gus within the Salamancas, which is further complicated when the cartel sends the shrewd [[Lalo Salamanca]] to oversee operations.\n\n== Concept and development ==\n[[Michael Mando]] said that he had been approached through his agent from ''Better Call Saul''{{'s}} casting directors about being in the show. After sending in an audition tape, he was flown to Los Angeles to meet with showrunners [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]] and perform a screen test. For Mando, he said it was \"love at first sight\" in working with the pair in how well they provided direction and feedback, and was notified about getting the part a few weeks later.<ref name=\"abq mando\" /> To prepare for Nacho, Mando spent time watching crime and criminology documentaries to understand the motivations of criminals, as well as catching up on the whole of ''Breaking Bad'', which he had not yet watched in its entirety before. Mando considered Nacho to be \"extremely intelligent and patient\" and would be a character that would have growth over the course of the show.<ref name=\"abq mando\">{{Cite news |last=Gomez |first=Adrian |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/544900/better-call-saul-star-delves-into-role.html |title=\u2018Better Call Saul\u2019s bad guy looks forward to season two |date=February 22, 2015 |work=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |access-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410180943/https://www.abqjournal.com/544900/better-call-saul-star-delves-into-role.html |archive-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Mando said that the showrunners gave little direction to the character, and instead \"They wanted to see what I would bring to the character\", allowing him to develop Nacho himself.<ref name=\"postmedia mando\" /> For part of that, he explored elements of [[Maya civilization|Mayan]] and [[Aztecs|Aztec]] cultures to bring to the character. He also brought some of the supervisial traits of his ''[[Orphan Black]]'' character Vic Schmidt into Nacho.<ref name=\"postmedia mando\">{{Cite web |url=https://o.canada.com/entertainment/television/quebec-actor-michael-mando-plays-better-call-saul-villian |title=Quebec actor Michael Mando plays Better Call Saul {{sic|nolink=y|villian}} |last=Strachan |first=Alex |date=February 4, 2015 |website=[[Postmedia News]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812060609/http://o.canada.com/entertainment/television/quebec-actor-michael-mando-plays-better-call-saul-villian |archive-date=August 12, 2018 |access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMando said that initially Nacho was going to have a larger role with Jimmy in the first season, being the season's \"[[Big Bad|big bad]]\", but as Gilligan and Gould wrote out the season, they made the character of [[Chuck McGill]] more of an antagonist for Jimmy, and so Nacho was placed on a slower path to be developed in later seasons. Mando said he felt this helped fit Nacho's character, waiting patiently for the right opportunity to make a move to get ahead.<ref name=\"vulture ignacio\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/03/better-call-saul-michael-mando-nacho-dilemma.html |title=Better Call Saul\u2019s Michael Mando on Nacho\u2019s Dilemma, His Bond With Mike, and the Mystery of Ignacio |last=Herzog |first=Kenny |date=March 7, 2016 |website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401045706/https://www.vulture.com/2016/03/better-call-saul-michael-mando-nacho-dilemma.html |archive-date=April 1, 2020 |access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/better-call-saul-michael-mando-was-supposed-to-be-season-1s-big-bad-heres-why-they-changed-that.html/ |title='Better Call Saul': Michael Mando Was Supposed to be Season 1's Big Bad. Here's Why They Changed That |last=Topel |first=Fred |date=March 9, 2020 |website=Showbiz Cheat Sheet |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311061141/https://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/better-call-saul-michael-mando-was-supposed-to-be-season-1s-big-bad-heres-why-they-changed-that.html/ |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Character biography ==\n[[File:Michael Mando by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|right|200px|[[Michael Mando]] portrays Nacho Varga in ''Better Call Saul'']]\nLittle is known of Nacho's background before the events of ''Better Call Saul''. While he spends some of his time helping his father Manuel with his [[upholstery]] business, most of Nacho's time is assisting in the Salamanca family's drug ring, which he does not speak of to his father.\n\n=== Season 1 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 1)}}\nWhile attempting to represent the Kettlemans, a family accused of embezzling $1.6 million, [[Saul Goodman|Jimmy McGill]] has a run-in with [[Tuco Salamanca]]. Tuco  has Nacho and other associates drag Jimmy to the desert to kill him. Nacho believes Jimmy's plea that he is a lawyer and convinces Tuco that killing an attorney would result in police scrutiny of the Salamanca family's drug business, so Tuco lets Jimmy go. Nacho approaches Jimmy about stealing the money from the Kettlemans, but Jimmy refuses. He warns the Kettlemans, who disappear from their home.  Nacho is the prime suspect and is arrested. He coerces Jimmy into helping clear his name and Jimmy locates the Kettlemans, which leads to Nacho's release.\n\nNacho engages in a side deal with Daniel Wormald (\"Pryce\"), who wants to sell pills stolen from the pharmaceutical company where he works. Daniel brings [[Mike Ehrmantraut]] as a bodyguard. When Nacho's payment is $20 short, Mike insists he pay the full amount. As Daniel and Mike leave, Mike explains that he knew Nacho was conducting the transaction without the Salamancas' knowledge and so had an incentive to make sure the deal went smoothly.\n\n=== Season 2 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 2)}}\nDaniel uses his drug money to buy a flashy [[Hummer]]. Mike refuses to participate in the next deal, so Daniel goes alone. Nacho takes the opportunity to learn Daniel's name and address. He later breaks into Daniel's house and steals the money back, along with a valuable collection of baseball cards. Daniel reports the collection's theft to the police, who discover an empty hiding place where Daniel hid the stolen drugs. Mike realizes his involvement will be uncovered if police continue to investigate, so he convinces Nacho to give Daniel the cards and $10,000 in exchange for the Hummer.\n\nNacho is impressed by Mike's candor and coolness under pressure.  As Tuco become increasingly volatile, potentially exposing the Salamanca organization, and the likelihood of his learning about Nacho's secret deals increases, Nacho decides to eliminate Tuco and tries to hire Mike to kill him.  Mike instead arranges a scenario where Tuco attacks him in view of police, leading to Tuco's arrest and conviction. [[Hector Salamanca]] has Nacho take Tuco's place in the organization. Mike becomes fearful that Hector may discover his role in removing Tuco from the family's operations.  He attempts to draw police attention to the Salamanca operation by hijacking one of the trucks used to smuggle drugs over the Mexican border, leaving the driver tied up at the side of the road and stealing the {{USD|250,000}} hidden in one of the tires. Nacho tells Mike that Hector covered up the hijacking by killing the Good Samaritan who stopped to aid the driver.\n\n=== Season 3 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 3)}}\nMike's actions lead to Hector looking for other routes to smuggle drugs, and he considers using Manuel's upholstery shop. Nacho objects, but fails to change Hector's mind.  To protect his father, Nacho reveals his involvement in the Salamanca organization. Manuel accepts Hector's initial payment after Nacho convinces him doing so is for his own safety. Nacho realizes Hector suffers from angina and decides to try to kill him by replacing his nitroglycerin with an ibuprofen [[placebo]] in the hopes of inducing a fatal heart attack.  Mike advises Nacho that if Hector dies, Nacho should immediately take the placebos from Hector and replace them with the real medication so that the cause of Hector's death won't be obvious.\n\nNacho succeeds in making the switch, but Hector does not die, so Nacho plans to shoot him.  Before he can act, Nacho is notified to attend a meeting with [[Gus Fring]], Juan Bolsa, and Hector. Bolsa informs Hector that cartel leader Don Eladio has decreed that since Hector's trucks are no longer viable for smuggling drugs, the cartel will make the transport of Hector's drugs via Gus's trucks a permanent arrangement. An outraged Hector has a stroke and falls to the ground unconscious.  Gus performs first aid while awaiting an ambulance, and succeeds in saving Hector's life, though he remains comatose.  Nacho takes the placebos from Hector and replaces them with the real medication.  Gus seems to realize that something is amiss, but says nothing.\n\n=== Season 4 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 4)}}\nBolsa tells Nacho that he and Arturo should run the Salamanca family while Hector is hospitalized.  Gus pays for Hector's specialized care to the point where his mental faculties are recovered and he can move the index finger of his right hand.  Gus reviews Hector's medical records and realizes there is no nitroglycerin in his system, meaning Nacho tried to kill him.  When Nacho and Arturo arrive at Gus' chicken farm to pick up their next cocaine shipment, Arturo takes six kilos instead of the agreed-upon five, as Nacho did on a previous occasion.  As they leave, Gus springs an ambush and suffocates Arturo with a plastic bag.  Gus reveals that he is aware of Nacho's attempt to kill Hector, and that if Nacho does not follow Gus' orders, Gus will inform the Salamancas.  Nacho, Victor, and Tyrus fake an ambush site on a remote road, shooting bullet holes in Nacho's car, setting the car on fire, and shooting Nacho.\n\nNacho is treated by veterinarian Dr. Caldera, who succeeds in saving his life.  Victor sells the drugs taken from Nacho to the Espinosas, a rival gang.  The Cousins arrive and Nacho falsely identifies the Espinosas as the ones who attacked him.  The Cousins attack the Espinosa compound, kill everyone inside, and recover the \"stolen\" drugs.  Nacho sees that by wiping out the Espinosas, Gus has secured more drug territory for himself, but does not yet see the full scope of Gus' plan.  Nacho goes to his father's house to recover, and Manuel takes him in despite being unhappy about Nacho's ties to the Salamancas.  After recovering, Nacho takes on a more prominent role in the Salamanca organization, but also keeps a safe with cash and fake Canadian IDs for himself and his father.  Nacho is surprised when Lalo Salamanca arrives to aid in running the business, and takes a stronger interest in the day-to-day details than Hector did.\n\n=== Season 5 ===\n{{See also|Better Call Saul (season 5)}}\nUnder Gus' orders, Nacho replaces some of the Salamanca cocaine supply with inferior, locally produced methamphetamine.  Buyer complaints lead Lalo to meet with Gus and Juan Bolsa.  Gus presents a cover story about Werner Ziegler, of whose activities Lalo was partly aware.{{efn|from \"[[Winner (Better Call Saul)|Winner]]\"}}  Gus claims Werner was working on a legitimate construction project at the chicken farm and stole cocaine, which Gus then replaced with meth.  The story explains the events of which Lalo is aware&nbsp;\u2013 Werner's work for Gus and escape, Mike's pursuit, and Werner's death.  Lalo accepts Gus' story and apology, but remains suspicious.\n\nGus threatens Manuel's life in order to coerce Nacho into providing inside information on the Salamancas. When police identify a Salamanca drug house and arrest Domingo, Nacho sneaks over rooftops to recover the drug stash before police enter, which impresses Lalo, who begins to take Nacho into his confidence.  Lalo is concerned that Domingo will talk in jail, so he and Nacho arrange to secure Domingo's release by providing police information on Gus's dead drops. Nacho reports this plan to Gus.  Gus decides to keep the dead drops in place, despite the likely loss of $700,000 in cash, because removing them would reveal to Lalo that someone is providing inside information about the Salamancas.\n\nGus, Victor, and Mike meet with Nacho and Nacho pretends not to recognize Mike. He reports on Lalo's plan to give police the locations of Gus's street dealers and Gus tells Nacho to report to Mike from now on. Nacho attempts to warn Mike about Gus's ruthlessness, but Mike reminds Nacho that he warned Nacho about the risk Nacho was taking when he attempted to kill Hector Salamanca.{{efn|from \"[[Expenses (Better Call Saul)|Expenses]]\"}} Mike secretly points the police to Lalo's car and its connection to the murder of Fred, the money wire store clerk.{{efn|from \"[[Winner (Better Call Saul)|Winner]]\"}} Nacho calls Mike to report Lalo's location. Mike uses a police radio and pretends to be an officer requesting a check of Lalo's licence plate, which causes police to converge on Lalo while he is driving and detain him.\n\nFrom jail, Lalo instructs Nacho to further disrupt Gus's business activities by burning down one of his restaurants, information Nacho relays to Mike. To preserve Nacho's role as his mole in the Salamanca organization, Gus and Nacho vandalize his flagship restaurant and set off an explosion that burns it down. Nacho enlists Jimmy to represent Lalo. Gus desires Lalo's release, so Mike provides Jimmy information on the investigation he did of Lalo under an assumed name. Jimmy uses the details to secure Lalo's release on US$7 million cash bail. Lalo has Jimmy pick up the cash funds for bail from a remote location in the desert. On his way back, Jimmy is attacked by gunmen but Mike arrives to protect him, and accompanies him to return to the city after Jimmy's car breaks down. Jimmy pays for Lalo's bail, giving him a cover story that omits the attack or Mike's involvement, and Lalo makes plans to return to Mexico due to increased interest on his alias. Meanwhile, Mike reports on the attack to Gus, and then also tells him that Nacho no longer wants to be Gus's spy, but Gus refuses to give up Nacho as an asset.\n\nNacho reports to Mike about driving Lalo to a dropoff point near Mexico the next day. After Lalo says goodbye to Hector, Nacho drives him to the same spot where Jimmy had picked up the bail money. Lalo realizes he had not seen Jimmy's car, and has Nacho help him search for it, soon discovering it in a ditch with bullet holes. Lalo has Nacho drive them back to the city and Jimmy's apartment. Lalo confronts Jimmy on his story as Kim watches, with Mike also listening from a nearby roof with a sniper rifle aimed on Lalo. Kim eventually tells Lalo to leave Jimmy alone and helps to vouch for Jimmy's story. Lalo leaves, but tells Nacho that they are now going to drive all the way into Mexico.\n\n=== ''Breaking Bad'' ===\nNacho did not appear in ''Breaking Bad'', but is named in the second-season episode \"[[Better Call Saul (Breaking Bad)|Better Call Saul]]\", the same episode that introduced Saul Goodman. In the episode, [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] and [[Jesse Pinkman]] attempt to coerce Saul into representing Badger after Badger is arrested for selling drugs. Unaware of who his gun-wielding captors are, Saul tries to pin blame on \"Ignacio\", who was later confirmed by ''Breaking Bad'' and ''Better Call Saul'' producers to be Nacho Varga.<ref name=\"vulture ignacio\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\nMando has received positive reviews for his portrayal of Nacho.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/10/michael-mando-better-call-saul-interview_n_6652668.html |title=Canadian Boy Makes Waves On 'Better Call Saul' |last=Jancelewicz |first=Chris |date=February 10, 2015 |website=[[HuffPost]] |location=Canada |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213090107/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/02/10/michael-mando-better-call-saul-interview_n_6652668.html |archive-date=February 13, 2015 |access-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notelist==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul/cast-crew/nacho-varga Nacho Varga] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Varga, Nacho}}\n[[Category:Better Call Saul characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional career criminals]]\n[[Category:Fictional gangsters]]\n[[Category:Fictional henchmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2015]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 5", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nacho_Varga"}
{"title_page": "John Atlantic Stephenson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n'''John Atlantic Stephenson''' (born 18 June 1829) was a [[Tyneside]] businessman and poet and amateur artist in the latter half of the 19th century. He was best known for his recitations.\n\n== Early life ==\nStephenson was born on [[Waterloo Day]], 18 June 1829 in mid-Atlantic.<ref  name=AllansMisc>{{cite web|title=Allan\u2019s Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings|url=https://archive.org/stream/allansillustrat00firgoog/allansillustrat00firgoog_djvu.txt}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Allan\u2019s Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings with lives, portraits and autographs of the writers, and notes on the songs.  Revised Edition|year=1891|publisher=Thomas & Gorge Allan, 18 Blackett Street, and 34 Collingwood Street, (Newcastle upon Tyne) \u2013 Sold by W. Allan, 80 Grainqer Street, Newcastle upon Tyne, B. Allan, North Shields and Walter Scott. London}}</ref>\n\nHe started work at Sowerby\u2019s Glass Works,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sowerby\u2019s Decorative Glass|url=http://www.20thcenturyglass.com/glass_encyclopedia/artdeco_glass/sowerby_glass/sowerbyglass_home.htm}}</ref> manufacturers of fine decorative glass items, at Gateshead and later moved on to a responsible post as representative for John Rogerson and Co. (who it is believed were brokers and shipping agents)\n\nHe was a founder member of the Bewick Club<ref>{{cite web|title=Bewick Club|url=http://www.tbrj.co.uk/bclub.htm|access-date=2012-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107090911/http://www.tbrj.co.uk/bclub.htm|archive-date=2011-01-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and held the post of honorary treasurer in the 1890s. He was an active member speaking at meetings, his humour mimicry and use of the local dialects of [[Tyneside]], [[Wearside]], [[Teesside]] and [[English of Northumbria|Northumberland]] made him very popular and in great demand. Some of his racy pieces also went down well on [[Tyneside]].\n\nHe was also a notable artist and he entered many of his paintings in the Club\u2019s annual exhibitions. These paintings were water colours and covered most aspects of rural life, including local scenes, farmhouses, half-ruined cottages, etc., and urban life in the form of scenes of Old Newcastle, many just before their demolition/removal.\n\n==Family==\nHis father,  also John Stephenson, was well known locally holding a responsible job as a superintendent in the Tyneside chemical industry. He was on his way to take up his post with the  [[East India Company]] in [[India]] when his son was born, in mid-Atlantic ocean, hence his middle name.\n\nHis mother Elizabeth (1804\u20131878), was a daughter of Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Goirdon) and Dr William Brummell, who was featured in several songs, in one [[William Purvis (Blind Willie)]] would sing of him and he is mentioned in [[William Oliver (songwriter)|William Oliver]]\u2019s \"[[Newcassel Props|The Newcassel Props]]\".\n\nThey travelled to India in the brig \"Argo\" and whilst in India at least three other children, Catherine Mary Layton (born c1836), Henry, and Indiana (sometimes referred to as Julianna \u2013 maybe at some stage it was transcribed wrongly), were born. \nThe family stayed in India for a period of 12 years before returning to Tyneside, and a further three further children were born after the family returned from India, Leonard, Albert and Alfred.\n\nIn the 1841 census, the family were living at Peak Hill (now [[Ravenscar, North Yorkshire|Ravenscar]]), [[Staintondale|Stainton Dale]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire]] where father was described as an agent for Peek Alum Works.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peek Alum Works|url=http://www.exnet.com/1995/12/18/science/science.html}}</ref>\n\nThe 1851 census shows them living at [[Gateshead]] with mother as a widow (The father died before Catherine\u2019s wedding in 1860), and according to the 1861 survey they were living at 11b Elswick East Terrace, [[Elswick, Tyne and Wear|Elswick]] with mother and just 3 children, John Atlantic having moved out by now.\n\n===Paintings===\n* The Dolphin House, Newcastle<ref>{{cite web|title=Dolphin House|url=http://www.artprints.org.uk/Landscape-Paintings/c7/p691/The-Dolphin-House-by-John-Atlantic-Stephenson/product_info.html}}</ref>\n*  Houses in Silver Street, Newcastle<ref>{{cite web|title=Silver Street|url=http://www.artprints.org.uk/Landscape-Paintings/c7/p692/Houses-in-Silver-Street-by-John-Atlantic-Stephenson/product_info.html}}</ref>\n\n===Poems and songs===\n*  Adam and Eve - A Wearside story\n*  Hawks's Men at the Battle of Waterloo\n*  The Postponed Goose \u2013 A Wearside tale\n*  A recollection of Ned Corvan\n*  A Tow for nowt \u2013 A Tyneside story \u2013 A recitation \u2013 about a keelman who wanted a free tow from Jarrow to the \"Mushroom\" jetty in\n\n== See also ==\n[[Geordie dialect words]]<br />\n[[Thomas Allan (publisher)|Thomas Allan]]<br />\n[[Allan's Illustrated Edition of Tyneside Songs and Readings]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606160110/http://mysite.verizon.net/cbladey/sang/bards.html#joewilson Bards of Newcastle]\n* [http://www.rolyveitch.20m.com/dialect_songwriters.html Wor Geordie songwriters]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/allansillustrat00firgoog/allansillustrat00firgoog_djvu.txt Allan\u2019s Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings]\n* [https://archive.is/20130221182509/http://www.glass-wiki.net/Sowerby.ashx?HL=sowerby Sowerby - Glass & Crystal]\n* [http://www.coastaltourism.co.uk/photo_gallery.htm Peek Alum Works photo gallery]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephenson, John Atlantic}}\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne (district)]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:20th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:1829 births]]\n[[Category:Geordie songwriters]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n'''John Atlantic Stephenson''' (born 18 June 1829) was a [[Tyneside]] businessman and poet and amateur artist in the latter half of the 19th century. He was best known for his recitations.\n\n== Early life ==\nStephenson was born on [[Waterloo Day]], 18 June 1829 in mid-Atlantic.<ref  name=AllansMisc>{{cite web|title=Allan\u2019s Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings|url=https://archive.org/stream/allansillustrat00firgoog/allansillustrat00firgoog_djvu.txt}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Allan\u2019s Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings with lives, portraits and autographs of the writers, and notes on the songs.  Revised Edition|year=1891|publisher=Thomas & Gorge Allan, 18 Blackett Street, and 34 Collingwood Street, (Newcastle upon Tyne) \u2013 Sold by W. Allan, 80 Grainqer Street, Newcastle upon Tyne, B. Allan, North Shields and Walter Scott. London}}</ref>\n\nHe started work at Sowerby\u2019s Glass Works,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sowerby\u2019s Decorative Glass|url=http://www.20thcenturyglass.com/glass_encyclopedia/artdeco_glass/sowerby_glass/sowerbyglass_home.htm}}</ref> manufacturers of fine decorative glass items, at Gateshead and later moved on to a responsible post as representative for John Rogerson and Co. (who it is believed were brokers and shipping agents)\n\nHe was a founder member of the Bewick Club<ref>{{cite web|title=Bewick Club|url=http://www.tbrj.co.uk/bclub.htm|access-date=2012-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107090911/http://www.tbrj.co.uk/bclub.htm|archive-date=2011-01-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> and held the post of honorary treasurer in the 1890s. He was an active member speaking at meetings, his humour mimicry and use of the local dialects of [[Tyneside]], [[Wearside]], [[Teesside]] and [[English of Northumbria|Northumberland]] made him very popular and in great demand. Some of his racy pieces also went down well on [[Tyneside]].\n\nHe was also a notable artist and he entered many of his paintings in the Club\u2019s annual exhibitions. These paintings were water colours and covered most aspects of rural life, including local scenes, farmhouses, half-ruined cottages, etc., and urban life in the form of scenes of Old Newcastle, many just before their demolition/removal.\n\n==Family==\nHis father,  also John Stephenson, was well known locally holding a responsible job as a superintendent in the Tyneside chemical industry. He was on his way to take up his post with the  [[East India Company]] in [[India]] when his son was born, in mid-Atlantic ocean, hence his middle name.\n\nHis mother Elizabeth (1804\u20131878), was a daughter of Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Goirdon) and Dr William Brummell, who was featured in several songs, in one [[William Purvis (Blind Willie)]] would sing of him and he is mentioned in [[William Oliver (songwriter)|William Oliver]]\u2019s \"[[Newcassel Props|The Newcassel Props]]\".\n\nThey travelled to India in the brig \"Argo\" and whilst in India at least three other children, Catherine Mary Layton (born c1836), Henry, and Indiana (sometimes referred to as Julianna \u2013 maybe at some stage it was transcribed wrongly), were born. \nThe family stayed in India for a period of 12 years before returning to Tyneside, and a further three further children were born after the family returned from India, Leonard, Albert and Alfred.\n\nIn the 1841 census, the family were living at Peak Hill (now [[Ravenscar, North Yorkshire|Ravenscar]]), [[Staintondale|Stainton Dale]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire]] where father was described as an agent for Peek Alum Works.<ref>{{cite web|title=Peek Alum Works|url=http://www.exnet.com/1995/12/18/science/science.html}}</ref>\n\nThe 1851 census shows them living at [[Gateshead]] with mother as a widow (The father died before Catherine\u2019s wedding in 1860), and according to the 1861 survey they were living at 11b Elswick East Terrace, [[Elswick, Tyne and Wear|Elswick]] with mother and just 3 children, John Atlantic having moved out by now.\n\n===Paintings===\n* The Dolphin House, Newcastle<ref>{{cite web|title=Dolphin House|url=http://www.artprints.org.uk/Landscape-Paintings/c7/p691/The-Dolphin-House-by-John-Atlantic-Stephenson/product_info.html}}</ref>\n*  Houses in Silver Street, Newcastle<ref>{{cite web|title=Silver Street|url=http://www.artprints.org.uk/Landscape-Paintings/c7/p692/Houses-in-Silver-Street-by-John-Atlantic-Stephenson/product_info.html}}</ref>\n\n===Poems and songs===\n*  Adam and Eve - A Wearside story\n*  Hawks's Men at the Battle of Waterloo\n*  The Postponed Goose \u2013 A Wearside tale\n*  A recollection of Ned Corvan\n*  A Tow for nowt \u2013 A Tyneside story \u2013 A recitation \u2013 about a keelman who wanted a free tow from Jarrow to the \"Mushroom\" jetty in\n\n== See also ==\n[[Geordie dialect words]]<br />\n[[Thomas Allan (publisher)|Thomas Allan]]<br />\n[[Allan's Illustrated Edition of Tyneside Songs and Readings]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606160110/http://mysite.verizon.net/cbladey/sang/bards.html#joewilson Bards of Newcastle]\n* [http://www.rolyveitch.20m.com/dialect_songwriters.html Wor Geordie songwriters]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/allansillustrat00firgoog/allansillustrat00firgoog_djvu.txt Allan\u2019s Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings]\n* [https://archive.is/20130221182509/http://www.glass-wiki.net/Sowerby.ashx?HL=sowerby Sowerby - Glass & Crystal]\n* [http://www.coastaltourism.co.uk/photo_gallery.htm Peek Alum Works photo gallery]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephenson, John Atlantic}}\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne (district)]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n[[Category:20th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:1829 births]]\n[[Category:Geordie songwriters]]\n