{"title_page": "List of Android app stores", "text_new": "The functionality of [[mobile device]]s running the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] operating system, the most used mobile operating system globally, can be extended using \"[[Mobile app|apps]]\" &ndash; specialized software [[Android software development|designed]] to offer users the means to use their devices for certain additional purposes. Such apps are compiled in the Android-native [[Android application package|APK file format]] which allows easy redistribution of apps to end-users.\n\nMost apps are distributed through [[Google]]'s [[Google Play|Play Store]] but many alternative software repositories, or [[app store]]s, exist. Alternative app stores use the \"Unknown Sources\" option of Android devices to install APK files directly via the Android Package Manager.\n\n== Google Play Store ==\n{{Main|Google Play}}\nThe Google Play Store (originally the Android Market), operated and developed by Google, serves as the official app store for the Android, allowing users to download apps developed with the [[Android SDK|Android software development kit (SDK)]] and published through Google. The store offers both free and paid apps. Apps exploiting hardware capabilities of a device can be targeted to users of devices with specific hardware components, such as a motion sensor (for motion-dependent games) or a front-facing camera (for online video calling). The Google Play store had over 50 billion app downloads in 2013 and has reached over 2.7 million apps published in 2017.\n\nAlthough bundled with most Android devices, the Play Store is only available on devices that [[Google Play#Compatibility|are certified within the \"Android Compatibility Program\"]]. As a result, manufacturers of so-called \"custom ROMs\", i .e. modified versions of Android, are not allowed to bundle Google apps, including the Play Store, with their software. Compatibility can be restored by installing the Google apps from another source, such as [[OpenGApps]], or using alternative app stores.\n\n== Manufacturer app stores ==\nIn addition to some manufacturers not creating certified compatible versions of Android, some manufacturers have decided to bundle their own app stores, either in addition to the Play Store or as a replacement. Such app stores include [[Samsung Galaxy Store]], which is installed on [[Samsung]] mobile devices alongside the Play Store and the [[Amazon Appstore]], which is installed instead of the Play Store on [[Amazon.com|Amazon's]] [[Fire Phone]] and [[Kindle Fire]]. In India, the Samsung Galaxy store is being powered by Indus App Bazaar and is offering a localized experience in 12 Indian languages to all its users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://telecom.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/samsung-ups-its-software-localisation-game-inks-app-store-deal-with-indusos/68406440|title=Samsung steps up software localisation game; inks app store deal with IndusOS|last=Khan|first=Danish|date=2019-03-15|website= Economic Times|}}</ref>The Amazon Appstore can also be installed on other Android devices by downloading it from the Amazon website.\n\n== Third-party app stores ==\nApp stores not relying on being preinstalled by a manufacturer exist as well. Apps offered through third-party app stores or websites that are created by parties not affiliated with the device or operating system are also third-party apps. \n\nNotable examples include [[Aptoide]], [[F-Droid]], [[GetJar]], HappyMod<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pc-tablet.com/how-to-download-happymod-app-on-your-android-device/|title=How to download HappyMod App on your Android device|last=Agarwal|first=Nitin|date=2020-03-14|website=PC-Tablet|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>, slide ME, Mobogenie Market, Itch.io, and Uptodown.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/tech/tired-google-play-check-alternative-181552505.html|title=Tired of Google Play? Check out these alternative Android app stores|last=Hill|first=Simon|date=September 24, 2016|work=[[Yahoo! Tech]]|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.androidauthority.com/uptodown-android-app-store-760878/|title=Alternative app store Uptodown launches its Android client|last=Gordon|first=Scott Adam|date=2017-03-31|work=Android Authority|access-date=2017-04-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidpit.com/best-google-play-store-alternative-app-stores?nocol=1|title=Best Google Play Store alternative app stores - AndroidPIT|last=Favre|first=Loie|date=June 26, 2015|work=AndroidPIT|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref>\n\nSuch app stores are often used by developers to distribute apps that are not allowed in the Play Store, for example because they allow users more access to the system or to offer apps for niche users, such as only [[free and open-source software]] (F-Droid) or [[indie game]]s (Itch.io). They might also serve to distribute \"hacked\" versions of paid apps for free.<ref name=\"yahoo\"/>\n\n== Reasons to use alternative app stores ==\nSome users prefer using alternative app stores to avoid using Google services as part of their philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.androidguys.com/2016/04/13/how-to-survive-android-without-google/|title=How to survive Android without Google|last=Schiwy|first=Nick|date=2016-04-13|website=AndroidGuys|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref> Alternative app stores may also be easier to navigate for users and allow them to find apps easier due to different algorithms or display of apps<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JL8GBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT15&dq=alternative+%22app+store%22+Android&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=alternative%20%22app%20store%22%20Android&f=false|title=Apps: Everything You Need To Know|last=Chiles|first=David|publisher=|year=2013|isbn=|pages=}}</ref> but users using either third-party app stores or Google Play cannot be certain that the apps they are installing have been checked for [[malware]] or [[computer virus]]es.<ref name=\"yahoo\"/>\n\nAnother reason for alternative app stores is that [[Google Play#Availability|full Google Play functionality is not available everywhere]]. For example, Chinese users cannot purchase apps on the Play Store, forcing them to use alternative app stores such as AppChina and Wandoujia.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zBFmBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA184&dq=alternative+%22app+store%22+Android&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=alternative%20%22app%20store%22%20Android&f=false|title=The Imaginary App|last=Miller|first=Paul D.|last2=Matviyenko|first2=Svitlana|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|year=2014|isbn=9780262027489|location=|page=184|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of mobile software distribution platforms]]\n\n{{Android|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:Mobile software distribution platforms]]\n", "text_old": "The functionality of [[mobile device]]s running the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] operating system, the most used mobile operating system globally, can be extended using \"[[Mobile app|apps]]\" &ndash; specialized software [[Android software development|designed]] to offer users the means to use their devices for certain additional purposes. Such apps are compiled in the Android-native [[Android application package|APK file format]] which allows easy redistribution of apps to end-users.\n\nMost apps are distributed through [[Google]]'s [[Google Play|Play Store]] but many alternative software repositories, or [[app store]]s, exist. Alternative app stores use the \"Unknown Sources\" option of Android devices to install APK files directly via the Android Package Manager.\n\n== Google Play Store ==\n{{Main|Google Play}}\nThe Google Play Store (originally the Android Market), operated and developed by Google, serves as the official app store for the Android, allowing users to download apps developed with the [[Android SDK|Android soft