it from the Amazon website.\n\n== Third-party app stores ==\nApp stores not relying on being preinstalled by a manufacturer exist as well. Notable examples include [[Aptoide]], [[F-Droid]], [[GetJar]], slide ME, Mobogenie Market, Itch.io, and Uptodown.<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/tech/tired-google-play-check-alternative-181552505.html|title=Tired of Google Play? Check out these alternative Android app stores|last=Hill|first=Simon|date=September 24, 2016|work=[[Yahoo! Tech]]|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.androidauthority.com/uptodown-android-app-store-760878/|title=Alternative app store Uptodown launches its Android client|last=Gordon|first=Scott Adam|date=2017-03-31|work=Android Authority|access-date=2017-04-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidpit.com/best-google-play-store-alternative-app-stores?nocol=1|title=Best Google Play Store alternative app stores - AndroidPIT|last=Favre|first=Loie|date=June 26, 2015|work=AndroidPIT|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref>\n\nSuch app stores are often used by developers to distribute apps that are not allowed in the Play Store, for example because they allow users more access to the system or to offer apps for niche users, such as only [[free and open-source software]] (F-Droid) or [[indie game]]s (Itch.io). They might also serve to distribute \"hacked\" versions of paid apps for free.<ref name=\"yahoo\"/>\n\n== Reasons to use alternative app stores ==\nSome users prefer using alternative app stores to avoid using Google services as part of their philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.androidguys.com/2016/04/13/how-to-survive-android-without-google/|title=How to survive Android without Google|last=Schiwy|first=Nick|date=2016-04-13|website=AndroidGuys|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref> Alternative app stores may also be easier to navigate for users and allow them to find apps easier due to different algorithms or display of apps<ref>{{Cite book|url