{"title_page": "Veronica Isala Eragu Bichetero", "text_new": "Veronica Isala Eragu Bichetero is a [[Uganda|Ugandan]] [[politician]] and lawyer  member of the [[Parliament of Uganda]] for [[Kaberamaido District|Kaberamaido district]] since 2016\n\nShe previously served as the Director and Senior Consultant at the EDG Venture Consult, Kampala from 2007-2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=413|title=Parliament of Uganda|website=www.parliament.go.ug|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Background and education ==\nShe was born  on 03-Aug-1953.   \n\nShe attended St Marys College, Aboke  for her  East African Certificate of Education ( EACE), in 1970 and    Dr. Obote College, Boroboro for her  East African Advanced Certificate of Education(EAACE) In 1972, she graduated from [[Makerere University]] in Uganda with a Bachelor of laws in 1976 and attained a Postgraduate Diploma in Legal Practice      from Law Development Centre, Kampala in 1978\n\n== Career and family ==\nSenior Fellow at the United States Institute of  Peace, Washington DC   from 2011-2012, Commissioner at   Uganda Human Rights Commission  from  2001-2007, she was also the Sole Partner  at Eragu & Co.Advocates, Kampala from 1998-2001 she was the  Managing Partner & Consultant  at Sentinel, Nairobi  from  1995-2001 she was as well the Senior Professional Consultant at UNICEF, Eastern and Southern Africa Regional Office, Nairobi from 1992-1994 Veronica was the  Director/General Manager at  Apollo Insurance Company, Kenya  from   1987-1991 Veronica also worked as a Claims Manager/Executive Manager at Kenya Commercial Insurance Corporation from   1983-1987,  Legal Practitioner   with the Rhodes & Rhodes, Lagos, Nigeria  from 1980-1981, Legal Secretary at National Insurance Corporation, Uganda from 1976-1980  she finally was elected as the Member of Parliament in Uganda from 2016 to date\n\n== Parliamentary duties ==\nBesides her duties as member of the Ugandan Parliament, she sits on the following [[parliamentary committees]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Committee Membership\n!Membership\n|-\n|COMMITTEE ON HUMAN RIGHTS\n|Member\n|-\n|COMMITTEE ON LEGAL AND PARLIAMENTARY AFFAIRS\n|Member\n|}\n\n\n<nowiki>{{Poli-Stub}}</nowiki> <nowiki>{{Stub}}</nowiki>\n", "text_old": "Veronica Isala Eragu Bichetero is a [[Uganda|Ugandan]] [[politician]] and lawyer  member of the [[Parliament of Uganda]] for [[Kaberamaido District|Kaberamaido district]] since 2016\n\nShe previously served as the Director and Senior Consultant at the EDG Venture Consult, Kampala from 2007-2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=413|title=Parliament of Uganda|website=www.parliament.go.ug|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Background and education ==\nShe was born  on 03-Aug-1953.   \n\nShe attended the   St Marys College, Aboke  for her  East African Certificate of Education ( EACE), in 1970 and    Dr. Obote College, Boroboro for her  East African Advanced Certificate of Education(EAACE) In 1972, she graduated from [[Makerere University]] in Uganda with a Bachelor of laws in 1976 and attained a Postgraduate Diploma in Legal Practice      from Law Development Centre, Kampala in 1978\n\n== Career and family ==\nSenior Fellow at the United States Institute of  Peace, Washington DC   from 2011-2012, Commissioner at   Uganda Human Rights Commission  from  2001-2007, she was also the Sole Partner  at Eragu & Co.Advocates, Kampala from 1998-2001 she was the  Managing Partner & Consultant  at Sentinel, Nairobi  from  1995-2001 she was as well the Senior Professional Consultant at UNICEF, Eastern and Southern Africa Regional Office, Nairobi from 1992-1994 Veronica was the  Director/General Manager at  Apollo Insurance Company, Kenya  from   1987-1991 Veronica also worked as a Claims Manager/Executive Manager at Kenya Commercial Insurance Corporation from   1983-1987,  Legal Practitioner   with the Rhodes & Rhodes, Lagos, Nigeria  from 1980-1981, Legal Secretary at National Insurance Corporation, Uganda from 1976-1980  she finally was elected as the Member of Parliament in Uganda from 2016 to date\n\n== Parliamentary duties ==\nBesides her duties as member of the Ugandan Parliament, she sits on the following [[parliamentary committees]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Committee Membership\n!Membership\n|-\n|COMMITTEE ON HUMAN RIGHTS\n|Member\n|-\n|COMMITTEE ON LEGAL AND PARLIAMENTARY AFFAIRS\n|Member\n|}\n\n\n<nowiki>{{Poli-Stub}}</nowiki> <nowiki>{{Stub}}</nowiki>\n", "name_user": "Mccapra", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veronica_Isala_Eragu_Bichetero"}
{"title_page": "Free Art Fair", "text_new": "{{cleanup|date=May 2011}}\n\nThe '''Free Art Fair''' was an exhibition of contemporary art works and performance art that took place in London in 2007, 2008, and 2009. Each fair culminated with all the art works being given away at the end. Jasper Joffe, the founder, claims he set up the fair to \"do something different from what everyone else is doing at this time of year and non-commercial, and something that excites people and values art not selling.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-art-idUKTRE49I1N320081019|title=Art lovers queue up to get hands on free artworks|date=19 October 2008|publisher=|via=uk.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nIn 2007 [[Jasper Joffe]] set up the first Free Art Fair with the participation of 25 artists all giving their art away for free in three empty shop spaces in Portman Village, near Marble Arch, London. It was described as the \"most radical departure from art fair commercialism\" that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/3668418/Art-sales-Frieze-Art-Fair.html|title=Art sales: Frieze Art Fair|first=Colin|last=Gleadell|date=8 October 2007|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Taking place in October at the same time as the [[Frieze Art Fair]] it was written about as an alternative asking questions of the market driven art fairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/oct/16/artmarkets-friezeartfair|title='If the work is free, is it art?'|date=16 October 2008|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the fair took place again near Marble Arch. It was reported that \u00a3100,000 of art was given away with people queuing up for two nights to get artwork by artists including [[Gavin Turk]] and [[Stella Vine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7680731.stm|title=Art lovers snap up free artwork|date=20 October 2008|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the fair moved to the [[Barbican Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barbican.org.uk/whats-on/art-design|title=Art & design - Barbican|website=www.barbican.org.uk}}</ref> 50 artists participated including [[Marlene Dumas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/|title=Home Page \u2013 The TLS|website=TheTLS}}</ref> one of the world's most expensive female artists by auction results at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elitechoice.org/2008/07/10/marlene-dumas-is-worlds-most-expensive-female-artist/|title=Marlene Dumas is World\u2019s Most Expensive Female Artist \u2013 Elite Choice|first=|last=Zolamarquis|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007 ===\nParticipating artists: Artists Anonymous, Centre Of Attention, Matthew Collings, Stuart Cumberland, Stephen Farthing, Rose Gibbs, Alex Hamilton, Peter Harris, Saron Hughes, Lee Johnson, Chantal Joffe, Jasper Joffe, Peter Lamb, Cathy Lomax, Amanda Loomes, Bruce McLean, Stephen Nelson, House of O\u2019Dwyer, Harry Pye, Danny Rolph, Bob & Roberta Smith, Terry Smith, Markus Vater, Edward Ward, Michael Ward\n\n=== 2008 ===\nParticipating artists Artists Anonymous, Centre of Attention, Matthew Collings, Jimmy Conway-Dyer, Sacha Craddock, Stuart Cumberland, Adam Dant, Stephen Farthing, Rose Gibbs, Luke Gottelier, Alex Hamilton, Peter Harris, Pablo Helguera, Saron Hughes, Lee Johnson, Sayshun Jay, James Jessop, Chantal Joffe, Jasper Joffe, Peter Lamb, Cathy Lomax, Amanda Loomes, Marta Marce, Bruce McLean, Alex Gene Morrison, Stephen Nelson, House of O\u2019Dwyer, Harry Pye, Danny Rolph, Martin Sexton, Bob & Roberta Smith, Terry Smith, Geraldine Swayne, Chris Tosic, [[Gavin Turk]], Markus Vater, Stella Vine, Michael Ward, Douglas White, Charlie Woolley.\nWith performances by: Laura Wilson, Frog Morris, Lee Campbell, Mark Dean Quinn, Dora Wade, Adrian Lee, Jenny Baines, Rebecca Birch, Calum F.Kerr, Jordan McKenzie, Charlotte Young, Victori Melody, Alex Staiger, Peter Bond, Sarah Turner, Daniel Lehan\n\n=== 2009 ===\nParticipating artists: Artists Anonymous, Phil Ashcroft, Centre of Attention, Maria Chevska, Matthew Collings, Jimmy Conway-Dyer Sacha Craddock, Stuart Cumberland, Adam Dant, Marlene Dumas, Stephen Farthing, [[Rose Finn-Kelcey]], Jaime Gili, Rose Gibbs, Alex Hamilton, Peter Harris, Pablo Helguera, Russell Herron, James Howard, Catrin Huber, Saron Hughes, Lee Johnson, Sayshun Jay, James Jessop, Jasper Joffe, [[Sonia Khurana]], Peter Lamb, Cathy Lomax, Amanda Loomes, Robin Mason, Bruce McLean, Hugh Mendes, Alex Gene Morrison, Chloe Mortimer, Stephen Nelson, House of O\u2019Dwyer, Henrik Potter, Harry Pye, Danny Rolph, Martin Sexton, Bob & Roberta Smith, Terry Smith, Eva Stenram, Matthew Stone, Geraldine Swayne, Chris Tosic, [[Josef O'Connor]], Markus Vater, Edward Ward, Michael Ward, Douglas White, Charlie Woolley. Performance Art curated by Lee Campbell and Frog Morris\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.freeartfair.com Official Free Art Fair website]\n* [http://www.saatchi-gallery.co.uk/blogon/view_video/5096/debate:_art_fairs_are_about_money_not_art \"Art Fairs are about money not art\" debate at Saatchi Gallery 2010]\n\n[[Category:Festivals in London]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Art fairs]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|date=May 2011}}\n\nThe '''Free Art Fair''' was an exhibition of contemporary art works and performance art that took place in London in 2007, 2008, and 2009. Each fair culminated with all the art works being given away at the end. Jasper Joffe, the founder, claims he set up the fair to \"do something different from what everyone else is doing at this time of year and non-commercial, and something that excites people and values art not selling.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-art-idUKTRE49I1N320081019|title=Art lovers queue up to get hands on free artworks|date=19 October 2008|publisher=|via=uk.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nIn 2007 [[Jasper Joffe]] set up the first Free Art Fair with the participation of 25 artists all giving their art away for free in three empty shop spaces in Portman Village, near Marble Arch, London. It was described as the \"most radical departure from art fair commercialism\" that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/3668418/Art-sales-Frieze-Art-Fair.html|title=Art sales: Frieze Art Fair|first=Colin|last=Gleadell|date=8 October 2007|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Taking place in October at the same time as the [[Frieze Art Fair]] it was written about as an alternative asking questions of the market driven art fairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/oct/16/artmarkets-friezeartfair|title='If the work is free, is it art?'|date=16 October 2008|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 the fair took place again near Marble Arch. It was reported that \u00a3100,000 of art was given away with people queuing up for two nights to get artwork by artists including [[Gavin Turk]] and [[Stella Vine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7680731.stm|title=Art lovers snap up free artwork|date=20 October 2008|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the fair moved to the [[Barbican Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barbican.org.uk/whats-on/art-design|title=Art & design - Barbican|website=www.barbican.org.uk}}</ref> 50 artists participated including [[Marlene Dumas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/|title=Home Page \u2013 The TLS|website=TheTLS}}</ref> one of the world's most expensive female artists by auction results at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elitechoice.org/2008/07/10/marlene-dumas-is-worlds-most-expensive-female-artist/|title=Marlene Dumas is World\u2019s Most Expensive Female Artist \u2013 Elite Choice|first=|last=Zolamarquis|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007 ===\nParticipating artists: Artists Anonymous, Centre Of Attention, Matthew Collings, Stuart Cumberland, Stephen Farthing,Rose Gibbs,